What you’re describing actually fits with some well-known things about how the brain works. It may feel unusual, but the basic mechanisms are real.

1. Memory can partially recreate bodily states

When you recall an experience vividly, the brain often reactivates some of the same neural networks that were active during the original experience. Studies using brain imaging show that:
	•	remembering a smell activates parts of the olfactory cortex
	•	imagining movement activates parts of the motor cortex
	•	recalling emotional experiences activates limbic system regions

So memory is not just a record—it can simulate aspects of the original state.

2. Expectation and placebo effects are powerful

Expectations can change perception and even bodily chemistry. In placebo research:
	•	people given inert pills sometimes experience real pain relief
	•	expectation can trigger endorphin release
	•	belief about a drug can alter how strong its effects feel

Your brain’s prediction systems help shape what you experience.

3. Cannabis can amplify internal imagery

Cannabis affects areas involved in:
	•	sensory perception
	•	memory retrieval
	•	attention to internal sensations

That can make mental imagery, memory, and bodily sensations feel stronger or more immersive, which might make it easier to recreate remembered states.

4. But it won’t fully reproduce another drug’s effects

Even though the brain can simulate aspects of past experiences, substances like morphine work through specific chemical pathways (opioid receptors, neurotransmitter changes, etc.). Memory and expectation can influence how things feel, but they can’t reproduce all of the physiological effects of a different drug.

5. This ability varies between people

Some people are especially good at vivid mental imagery or interoception (awareness of internal body sensations). That can make recalled experiences feel surprisingly real.

⸻

So what you’re describing—recreating sensations by combining memory, expectation, and current sensations—is consistent with how predictive processing in the brain works. The brain is constantly blending:
	•	incoming sensory signals
	•	memories of past experiences
	•	expectations about what should happen

to generate what you feel in the moment.

If you’re curious, there’s another related phenomenon called state-dependent memory, where memories are easier to access when you’re in a similar physical or emotional state to when they were formed. That sometimes plays a role in experiences like the one you described.